**Caroline Elizabeth Polachek** (born June 20, 1985) is an American singer, producer, and songwriter. Raised in [Connecticut](Connecticut), Polachek co-founded the [pop](indie)(indie pop) band [Chairlift](Chairlift (band)) while studying at the [of Colorado](University)(University of Colorado). The duo emerged from the late-2000s [Brooklyn](Brooklyn) music scene with the [hit](sleeper)(sleeper hit) "Bruises".

Following her time in the band, she worked on the solo projects **Ramona Lisa** and **CEP** before embarking on a career under her own name after Chairlift disbanded in 2017. Her debut studio album, [*Pang*](Pang (album)) (2019), featured an [avant-pop](avant-pop) sound and was released to critical acclaim, in particular the single "[Hot You're Hurting My Feelings](So)(So Hot You're Hurting My Feelings)". In 2023, Polachek released the album *[I Want to Turn Into You](Desire,)(Desire, I Want to Turn Into You)* equally to critical acclaim.

Polachek has worked extensively with other artists, collaborating with [Orange](Blood)(Dev Hynes), [Fischerspooner](Fischerspooner), [Sbtrkt](Sbtrkt), [and the Queens](Christine)(Christine and the Queens), [XCX](Charli)(Charli XCX), [Grimes](Grimes), and the British music collective [Music](PC)(PC Music), as well as writing material for [Beyoncé](Beyoncé) ("[Angel](No)(No Angel (Beyoncé song))").

## Early life

Polachek was born in [Manhattan](Manhattan), New York City, on June 20, 1985, to James Montel Polachek (1944–2020), a scholar for Chinese history and trained classical musician, and Elizabeth Allan. Her family relocated to [Tokyo](Tokyo), Japan, where she lived between the ages of one and six, and later settled in [Connecticut](Greenwich,)(Greenwich, Connecticut), where Polachek started singing choir in the third grade.
